<!-- Content -->

<p>
<b>Le Vin du solitaire</b><br>
</p>

<p>
Le regard singulier d'une femme galante<br>
Qui se glisse vers nous comme le rayon blanc<br>
Que la lune onduleuse envoie au lac tremblant,<br>
Quand elle y veut baigner sa beaut&eacute; nonchalante;<br>
</p>

<p>
Le dernier sac d'&eacute;cus dans les doigts d'un joueur;<br>
Un baiser libertin de la maigre Adeline;<br>
Les sons d'une musique &eacute;nervante et c&acirc;line,<br>
Semblable au cri lointain de l'humaine douleur,<br>
</p>

<p>
Tout cela ne vaut pas, &ocirc; bouteille profonde,<br>
Les baumes p&eacute;n&eacute;trants que ta panse f&eacute;conde<br>
Garde au coeur alt&eacute;r&eacute; du po&egrave;te pieux;<br>
</p>

<p>
Tu lui verses l'espoir, la jeunesse et la vie,<br>
&mdash; Et l'orgueil, ce tr&eacute;sor de toute gueuserie,<br>
Qui nous rend triomphants et semblables aux Dieux!<br>
</p>
<p>&mdash; <i>Charles Baudelaire</i></p><br /><p>
<b>The Wine of the Solitary</b><br>
</p>

<p>
The strange look of a lady of pleasure <br>
Turned slyly toward us like the white beam <br>
Which the undulous moon casts on the trembling lake <br>
When she wishes to bathe her nonchalant beauty;<br>
</p>

<p>
The last bag of crowns between a gambler's fingers;<br>
A lustful kiss from slender Adeline;<br>
The sound of music, tormenting and caressing,<br>
Resembling the distant cry of a man in pain,<br>
</p>

<p>
All that is not worth, O deep, deep bottle, <br>
The penetrating balm that your fruitful belly <br>
Holds for the thirsty heart of the pious poet;<br>
</p>

<p>
You pour out for him hope, and youth, and life<br>
&mdash; And pride, the treasure of all beggary,<br>
Which makes us triumphant and equal to the gods!<br>
</p>

<p>
&mdash; William Aggeler, <i>The Flowers of Evil</i> (Fresno, CA: Academy Library Guild, 1954)<br>
</p>

<br>

<p>
<b>The Wine of the Solitary Man</b>
</p>

<p>
The love-glance of a courtesan that swims <br>
With undulating ray like that the moon <br>
Sends to the waiting, tremulous lagoon <br>
Where she's about to lave her languid limbs:<br>
</p>

<p>
The last few florins in a gambler's fingers: <br>
The lustful kiss of slender Adeline: <br>
A haunting tune that wheedles and malingers, <br>
Wherein all human anguish seems to pine:<br>
</p>

<p>
All these aren't worth, O bottle kind and deep, <br>
The penetrating balms that swell your paunch <br>
The pious poet's wounded heart to staunch.<br>
</p>

<p>
You pour him hope, youth, life, and healing sleep &mdash; <br>
And pride, all Beggary's diadem and treasure, <br>
By which our triumphs with the Gods' we measure.<br>
</p>

<p>
&mdash; Roy Campbell, <i>Poems of Baudelaire</i> (New York: Pantheon Books, 1952)<br>
</p>

<br>

<p>
<b>Le Vin du solitaire</b><br>
</p>

<p>
the wildering glances of a harlot fair<br>
seen gliding toward us like the silver wake<br>
of undulant moonlight on the quivering lake<br>
when Phoebe bathes her languorous beauty there;<br>
</p>

<p>
the last gold coins a gambler's fingers hold;<br>
the wanton kiss of love-worn Adeline,<br>
the wheedling songs that leave the will supine<br>
&mdash; like far-off cries of sorrow unconsoled &mdash;<br>
</p>

<p>
all these, o bottle deep, were never worth <br>
the pungent balsams in thy fertile girth<br>
stored for the pious poet's thirsty heart;<br>
</p>

<p>
thou pourest hope and youth and strength anew,<br>
&mdash; and pride, this treasure of the beggar-crew, <br>
that lifts us like triumphant gods, apart!<br>
</p>

<p>
&mdash; Lewis Piaget Shanks, <i>Flowers of Evil</i> (New York: Ives Washburn, 1931)<br>
</p>

<br>
<!-- Navigation -->

<div id="bottom">

<h3>Navigation</h3>

<p class="commentary">
Two editions of <i>Fleurs du mal</i> were published in Baudelaire's lifetime &mdash; one in 1857 and an expanded edition in 1861. "Scraps" and censored poems were collected in <i>Les &Eacute;paves</i> in 1866. After Baudelaire died the following year, a "definitive" edition appeared in 1868.
</p>

<ul>
	<li><a href="1857-table-of-contents">1857 Fleurs du mal</a><div class="nav-commentary">First edition with 100 poems</div></li>
	<li><a href="1861-table-of-contents">1861 Fleurs du mal</a><div class="nav-commentary">Second edition missing censored poems but including new ones</div></li>
	<li><a href="1866-les-epaves-table-of-contents">1866 Les &Eacute;paves</a><div class="nav-commentary">Twenty-three "scraps" including the poems censored from the first edition</div></li>
	<li><a href="1868-table-of-contents">1868 Fleurs du mal</a><div class="nav-commentary">Comprehensive edition published after Baudelaire's death</div></li>
	<li><a href="alphabetical-listing">All Poems (Alphabetical)</a><div class="nav-commentary">Every poem from each edition</div></li>
	<li><a href="audio/">Audio</a><div class="nav-commentary">Readings of Baudelaire mostly in French</div></li>
